premise_source_doc_sentence: The creation of ASPD and DPD was driven by the fact that many of the classic traits of psychopathy were impossible to measure objectively .

The Psychopathy Checklist or Hare Psychopathy Checklist-Revised , now the Psychopathy Checklist -- revised  (  PCL-R  )  , is a psychological assessment tool most commonly used to assess the presence of psychopathy in individuals .

The PPI was developed by Scott Lilienfeld and Brian Andrews to assess these traits in non-criminal  (  e.g. university students  )  populations , though it is still used in clinical  (  e.g. incarcerated  )  populations as well .
The concept of psychopathy continues to be influential through forming parts of the diagnosis of antisocial personality disorder , the Psychopathy Checklist , and public perception .
In contrast to other psychopathy measures , such as the Hare Psychopathy Checklist  (  PCL  )  , the PPI is a self-report , rather than interview-based , assessment .
